"Model UN was an activity that I started in high school. When I got to college, I was a biology major at first, so my idea of how my year would go did not include model UN. I figured it was something fun, but something that I did in high school. But then, I wanted to do more beyond schoolwork, and UMass had a Model UN club. It was the only club I joined my freshman year. I really enjoyed meeting people beyond my major, and interacting with people about what’s going on in the world. UMass allowed me to go to different conferences; I even left the country and went to Canada on one of our trips. I debated with other people from multiple different colleges, so I found a community at UMass, but also one that extended beyond UMass. It made me think about my place in the world and how all of us fit in. I really appreciated the chance to know more people beyond just my major and just my floor, so that’s why I stuck with it.⁣
⁣
Choosing to switch from biology to public health and anthropology had a lot to do with Model UN, because public health is the science side of biology — which I really enjoyed — but it also has that human aspect, and anthropology is all about studying people and how they work and how they operate. So, if you want to bring the health and science field to any group, person or individual, you have to know how they think, work, and operate. Switching my major from biology to public health, and then anthropology as well, allowed me to still interact with the cause and effect and the logic and organization of biology. Biology really structures the world and life and the way we think, but then public health allowed me to see the impact of that, and anthropology was the icing on the cake that allowed everything to be synthesized.⁣" — Althea Turley, class of 2020, public health sciences and anthropology major

"Being able to live near Boston [at the Mount Ida campus] to do my internship at Brigham and Women’s Hospital was so great. I was a little nervous at first because it was a new experience, but once I got here, it felt so safe and the campus is beautiful and the community is very positive. The veterinary technician students were housed here in New Hall, so I got the opportunity to meet them and get to know them. It was nice because while the campus was still pretty empty for the most part, whenever you came out of New Hall, there were always students hanging out in the lobby, which indicated that there was definitely still life on the campus. It was also really cool to get to know what it was like for them to live here, because most of them had been here for at least three years before. They guided me through the ins and outs of the campus.⁣
⁣
I also really liked being near Boston and learning how to commute, especially because I was thinking how I really want to live in Boston but never knew what it would be like. It’s a big deal to come out of graduating and get a job somewhere that’s foreign to you, so being able to be here gave me the opportunity to try that out and see if this would be the right fit for me before I ventured into real life post-grad.⁣
⁣
I would tell anyone who moves to Mount Ida to be proactive, don’t be afraid to ask questions, and explore the new area if they’re not familiar with it. It’s a great opportunity to, in a way, “study abroad” but not super far away from where campus is. You still have access to all the resources at UMass Amherst, so it’s not like those leave, but you also have all the city life. Something that I really enjoyed was being able to try different restaurants, or have my friends come over from UMass and explore the city together. It’s a really great way to bring a little bit of Amherst with you while also trying something new." — Ashley Rice, class of 2020, public health sciences and Spanish major

"When I joined the Association of Diversity in Sports, I didn’t really know anything about it. Now it’s opened my eyes to a whole new world, and I want to end up in a diversity and inclusion part of sports. My dream is to make sports more accessible to play and to watch, and my fairy tale is to become a billionaire and create my own non-profit that brings sports equipment to underdeveloped areas and countries, making it sustainable for them to be able to play.⁣
⁣
This department also really emphasizes family. Between the students, the clubs, and the faculty and staff, we’re a really close-knit group. My neighbors five houses up the street and five houses across the street are all Sports Management students; we eat, breathe, sleep together. Our professors are absolutely amazing, and always have their doors open. We’re each other’s biggest support group." — Madison Perlmutter, class of 2020, sports management major

"I came into college studying chemistry, but I felt like there was something missing, that just chemistry alone wasn’t enough to satisfy my curiosity. I spent the first two weeks of college trying to decide which major was right for me, and I finally landed on chemical engineering.
.
I had an internship with @umassials last summer; it was a wonderful experience. When you think of chemical engineering, a lot of chemical engineers like to split it up into subsets. You have the subset that deals with traditional chemicals, the subset that deals with environmental stuff, and you have the materials aspect. The materials aspect is what I was interested in, which is why the IALS internship was such a big deal to me.
.
I’m the type of person who likes to observe; I’m very analytical, and I think about things very deeply. In the future, I’m planning on going to graduate school to likely get a masters degree in chemical engineering, and I envision myself being a leader of an engineering team. I want to look at the big picture, think about what pieces we need, and become the architect of an entire project."
.
Telvin Abariga, class of 2020, studying chemical engineering with a concentration in material science with @umassengineering and economics with @sbs_umass

"I declared my major and concentration before I even got to UMass because growing up I’ve always enjoyed being outdoors and I knew that the natural world was threatened by a lot of things. It made me really sad and scared for our future, so I chose the concentration specifically because I felt like there was this sense of compassion that was lacking toward wildlife. They’re so innocent, and not causing anything, but they’re ultimately facing all of the repercussions of climate change due to our carelessness. I also just knew that UMass has an incredible natural sciences department, and this major specifically is one of the top in the country.
🌱
With everything going on, it’s easy to instill fear in people about climate change. It’s so easy to be like, “These are the horrible things that are happening, and we’re pretty much doomed, but you can still do something, kind of.” Instead of doing that, I feel like a lot of professors inspire us to take action and do so in a way that’s more like, “Look at this really cool thing that exists in the world and that we get to learn about. If climate change keeps progressing, we can’t learn about it anymore.” The department inspires us to research things, and learn more on our own. I’ve had a lot of projects in which there’s a basic guideline, but if you approach the professors with an idea that you’re passionate about, they encourage you to present work that you’re passionate about and learn about things that you like." — Kate Keery, class of 2020, natural resources conservation major

"What I really like about the @umassamhersttheater department is that nobody is ever going to tell you 'no.' If you show a willingness to do something, they’ll reward that. .
When I first started working in the department, I thought I wanted to go into lighting design. I started cultivating relationships with our faculty who I now basically consider my colleagues, which is really cool. I worked on a show called 'The Lily’s Revenge' as the master electrician, where I ran the crew. It was a lot of fun to prove my dedication off of the get-go, and say I’m here, and I’m serious about this.
.
From there, I did more lighting and found that my area in lighting was console programming. That involves programming all the lights — a designer is designing, they’re talking to you, you’re turning lights on and off, setting levels, recording cues, that whole thing. Through that, I found that I really enjoyed tasks that involved an organizational mindset. I also jumped through sound engineering and projection design, and all of these things led me to stage management, which is my focus right now.
.
I always joke that production management is like problem-solving as a sport. I love problem solving, so it works out very well.
.
After the summer, I’m hoping that if all goes as planned, I’ll actually be working as stage manager in an Off Broadway/Broadway contract." Tom Kelleher, class of 2020, studying theater @umasshfa

"Two pieces of advice I can give when it comes to founding your own organization is: not doing it alone and patience.
.
With PAC (Prison Abolition Collective) and RJ (Restorative Justice Task Force), even though I co-founded them, the emphasis would be that I’m a 'co,' because I did not do that at all alone. When I say alone, I mean taking on all the leadership, all the labor, and the stress of it. .
I would say the biggest thing is making sure that you have a community to fall back on. You don’t want it to be like, 'Hey, I built this thing, come join me.' It should be, 'Hey, I have this idea. Who can build this with me?' When we’re more inclusive, more people want to be a part of it; more people are open to it.
.
Patience really is key, because when you really do care about something, it’s about setting the intention, and about doing what you can now with what you have. The future will come when it comes."
.
Nathalie Amazan, class of 2020, studying political science and legal studies with a letter of specialization in social justice w/ @sbs_umass , and Afro-American studies w/ @umasshfa

"I think when I simultaneously started a couple different endeavors in the same year — I became a tour guide, I joined a sorority, and I started participating in Alternative Spring Break — that helped me get my feet on the ground running. I ended up meeting a ton of really good friends, made great social connections, and had the opportunity to really flourish as a person and get to know other people. Looking back on it, I had really blossomed, and I think I don’t give myself enough credit for that." — Jill Drummy, class of 2020, public health sciences major⁣

"Working at @umasssweets is probably the best job I will ever have in my entire life. Many former co-managers say that. Everyone has these dream jobs, but this really is the dream job. We’re our own bosses and we make our own decisions, and we can actually change the way that we do our work. For example, we at one point didn’t compost, and now we compost.
🍦
Working in a student business has taught me a lot about responsibility, time management, professionalism, and a lot of life skills.
🍦
When I first got hired, we had a lot of culture changes happen throughout the business to help everyone make friends. I thought, what if we went away for the weekend? We all went away together, and got so close, and had this amazing bonding experience. These are people who I consider my bestest friends; I’ve lived with a couple of them, I’ve gone on vacation with them, and keep in contact with so many of them. We’ve kept that tradition ever since."
🍦
Sam Kennedy, class of 2020, majoring in economics and legal studies in @sbs_umass

"When I first came here from South Korea, I couldn’t speak fluently. I was isolated from society because of the language barrier. But then, a Korean woman who didn’t speak any English came to me and asked for help. That was a turning point. I thought, 'What if I was that woman that needed help, who didn’t know where to go?' I looked around for the English teaching community, and started out at Greenfield Middle School taking adult evening classes. I enrolled in Greenfield Community College in 2011, and in the meantime continued to help Korean immigrants. I enrolled at UWW in September 2018, and in December, UWW became the first university in the nation to come up with the Translation/Interpreting bachelor’s degree. This educational journey took me 46 years to get here. [Now], I’m going to reach my educational summit, which I never thought would be possible. Talk about waiting; all good things come to those who wait." See kyung Pak, class of 2020, Translation and Interpreting through University Without Walls.

This isn't how we pictured the semester, but we couldn't be prouder of #UMass2020 for how you've persevered. We are thrilled to pay tribute to a few members of this graduating class starting today.⁣
⁣
"One of my favorite parts of my education has been seeing people at their worst get better. There is something so valuable about being the face of health and working to alleviate somebody’s pain and suffering. Watching that continuum of care, watching that growth, has just been remarkable to see. Through nursing school I was able to hold somebody’s hand in death, as well as somebody giving birth, and the fact that I was given those opportunities means I am now able to reflect on them throughout the rest of my nursing practice. It’s changed my life, and given me so much more of an outlook on how to care." — Carl McDonald, class of 2020, nursing major⁣

We understand many students want to return to campus to collect their belongings, so we are initiating a systematic, sequenced move-out process to accommodate these requests.
▪️
▪️
The process will begin this weekend, March 21-22, for selected students, and continue on a rolling basis.
▪️
▪️
Students in the first phase of the move-out have been informed via email. If you didn't receive an email, then you will be scheduled for a different weekend.
▪️
▪️
We appreciate your patience as we do this in a methodical and safe way for everyone.

It is with a heavy heart that we announce, because of the ongoing prohibition of large gatherings and our own efforts to mitigate the spread of coronavirus/COVID-19, our 2020 Commencement, which was scheduled for Friday, May 8th, and all commencement weekend activities, will be postponed.
▪️
▪️
We realize what an important moment this day is for our students, their families, and the entire UMass community. Unfortunately, at this point, we do not have a definitive answer for how and when we will honor our graduates, but we can assure you that we will.
▪️
▪️
At this moment, we're asking for input from our students for whom this day means so much. Those wishing to share ideas can email them to commencement@umass.edu. As our plans take shape, we will keep the campus updated.

We’ve got a few updates on COVID-19 as it relates to the UMass Amherst community — Check out our latest story for more info, and thanks so much for your patience as the situation unfolds. We hear you, and we are doing our best to relay information as soon as we have it!

A message from Chancellor Subbaswamy, as he announces a series of campus measures at UMass Amherst that are in coordination with efforts across the state, nation, and world to contain the coronavirus COVID-19. “For us to work through this trying period, we will need to support each other, remain flexible, and prepare ourselves for disruption and change...It’s a difficult time for everyone. But we are well prepared to successfully manage through this period—together.”
